e late 1990s to its realization as an autonomous territory in 2009 and beyond. Goett argues that despite significant gains in multicultural recognition, Afro-Nicaraguan Creoles continue to grapple with the day-to-day violence of capitalist intensification, racialized policing, and drug war militarization in their territories. Activists have responded by adopting a politics of autonomy based on race pride, territoriality, self-determination, and self-defense. Black Autonomy shows how this political radicalism is rooted in African diasporic identification and gendered cultural practices that women and men use to assert control over their bodies, labor, and spaces in an atmosphere of violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBlacksxGovernment relationsxNicaraguaxMonkey Point. 0aBlacksxPolitics and governmentxNicaraguaxMonkey Point. 0aBlackszNicaraguazMonkey PointxGovernment relations. 0aBlackszNicaraguazMonkey PointxPolitics and government. 0aCommunity activistsxNicaraguaxMonkey Point. 0aCommunity activistszNicaraguazMonkey Point. 0aMulticulturalismxPolitical aspectsxNicaragua. 0aMulticulturalismxPolitical aspectszNicaragua. 0aWomen, BlackxPolitical activityxNicaraguaxMonkey Point. 0aWomen, BlackxPolitical activityzNicaraguazMonkey Point. 4aAfrodescendants. 4aCentral America. 4aLatin America. 4aNicaragua. 4aactivism. 4aautonomy. 4agender. 4amulticultural rights. 4arace. 4aviolence. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360055340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503600553423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503600553.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aG